We cut nature into pieces,
in the most convenient way,

metadata.name: Dopamine Dreams #161
metadata.description:
Dopamine is a chemical released in the brain that makes you feel good.

Dopamine Dreams is an exploration of using patterns and geometric forms to create something that also makes you feel good; to create something that feels natural, as if it has sprung from the ground or appeared in the sky.  

In this work, there is a conversation happening between two modes for drawing the same grid. One is tight, geometric and calm. The other is loose, loopy and excited. They overlap, interlace and compete to fill the space.  One cannot exist without the other. Balance is the the key. Between them they create a landscape in which to dream. 

Generative artwork by AutoEclectus

Controls in live mode:
- After animation stops, press [s] to save a png

@autoeclectus everywhere - Twitter, Instagram and Masterdon. 
https://autoeclectus.art

metadata.name: Staccato #271
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

Containing just three basic repeating shapes, 'Staccato' is inspired by minimalist geometric art.
Each 'Staccato' output forms a bold, colorful and (hopefully) pleasing design.

In live mode:
Click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear. Click this button to download a 1500x2000px PNG.

metadata.name: Lua #53
metadata.description:
"I journey to the world of the moon,
Where life is less burdensome,
Where all gaze upon me, unaware
Of my presence in this lunar realm.

Yet darkness occasionally envelops me,
Leaves me lost and unsure.
But in the end, it is worth it all,
For on the moon, I am admired and loved,
Connected to others, despite being unseen."

~ Eduxdux + GPT

Made with p5.js, chroma.js and p5.grain

metadata.name: Gkrint #40
metadata.description:
Gkrint is a celebration of minimalism, colour, and space using the humble grid, a foundation of generative art, and movement. Through this collaboration, Ballzerino and George explore the relationships between these elements.

Inspired by the timeless principles of Bauhaus design, Ballzerino carefully curated custom colour palettes and selected geometric shapes, while George encoded the creative process into an algorithm, bringing the compositions to life, and putting the CPU to work finding new and unexpected compositions within our framework.

Gkrint is Ballzerino's genesis generative art drop.

Controls:
SPACE - pause / resume
click (or tap) - change colour selection (within same palette)
hold 'f' - speed up animation

Tested on Windows / Mac / iOS / Android. Chrome recommended for the best experience.

metadata.name: 山水畫 #117
metadata.description:
山水, literally mountain and water, i.e. landscape. Instead ink, brush, and rice paper, rectangles, p5js and screen, explores not code realism, but code-ism composition and form. 畫, painting, each landscape is performed, unknowing the exact, as is Chinese landscape painting, the painter, paints his or her fictional landscape. Here my code and the hash paints each landscape with a constrained brush, that is rectangles. 

An important aesthetic factor in Chinese landscape painting is the negative space. Here the positive-negative relation is akin to ying-yang, that in Tai-Chi (太極), there are no absolute positive-yang and absolute negative-ying. At the edge of one polar extreme, signals the change towards the other. Like midday, the sun will set. And between midday and midnight, there is plenty of grey. 

I am sorry “life has no scores” will not be my final drop just yet. Precisely since life has no fixed scores to follow. In preparation for my solo ink show in march, I look towards generative art to give me inspiration. Instead of code imitating brush, my brush and mind aims to discover my own fictional landscapes through code and hashes. 

To see mountains, where there are not any, just the concept of them. I hope you enjoy the mountain view as I will. fxhash is more than a community, when our path crosses, we create art together.  

Press ‘2’ to save png.

Tested on chrome, preview images might be compressed.
